 sure isn't going to absorb many neutrons with THAT cross-section.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Yes, I am aware of the differences between thermal and fast neutron cross-sections.  One piece of information I am looking for is whether or not the fast cross-section is reduced by high temperatures.  I suspect it is not, but have not found any verifying data yet.   At high temps, such as 25,500K, the thermal cross section of U235 drops from 583 barns to 81.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The fast cross-section of U235 is about 10 barns, from what I have found.  If that also drops with temperature, a moderator in the chamber is essential, and I'll probably use a lot of hydrogen inside the lightbulb.  I doubt the fast cross-section drops with temps, though, because scientists were able to light up these vortexes back in the 60's.  Plus, it would make lighting a nuclear bomb a much harder task.... <br>
<br>
 <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
