Oh, I have also been thinking about cooling the buffer gas so it can be re-pumped.  The heat-exchanger can be either a full temperature/pressure design, using a small silica window to radiate the heat into coolant hydrogen.  The other possibility is to expand the buffer gas to drop the temps, then use <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.lanl.gov/worldview/news/releases/archive/00-064.shtml"> lithium-filled heatpipes </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> to dump the energy into a coolant flow.  <br>
<br>
Those heat pipes will come in VERY handy in the construction of the Liberty Ship thrusters.  I can think of a few places where the ability to move massive amounts of heat energy quickly at &quot;low&quot; temps will be very useful.  <br>
