<br>
In the meantime, I took a few minutes to look at the current state of the art in semi-sumbersible ships, and BOY, do things look good there!<br>
<br>
First, take a look at <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.dockwise.com/start-fleet.html"> this </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> page, of a company which has an entire FLEET of semi-submersibles.  The most interesting thing, though, is <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.dockwise.com/news/pdf_jumboised_blue_marlin/jumboised_blue_marlin.pdf"> this .pdf </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> of the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Blue Marlin </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> heavy-lift semi-submersible, which is due to be enlarged to truly heroic dimensions next year.  <br>
<br>
I imagine the 63 meter wide deck of this monster would be PLENTY big enough to launch and land a Liberty Ship, and it can put 15 meters of water over the deck to boot!<br>
<br>
Now, I was looking for heavy lift cranes, to handle the 1000 ton weight of the Liberty Ship cargo pod, and made another pleasant discovery: There are ships with cranes almost that big already!  Taking a look at <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.huisman-itrec.com/"> this site </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> you discover a company which builds Heavy Lift Mast Cranes, designed to operate in tandem.  They are building a pair of these behemoths that can lift 800 tons each, for a combined lift of 1600 tons.  I suspect they could easily build something to handle the Liberty Ship's needs.<br>
<br>
Nice!  <br>
<br>
I swear, every time I look at any aspect of the Liberty Ship Launch System (I just made that up, like it?) I find that there already exists systems that handle the requirements of that aspect effortlessly.<br>
<br>
Ain't technology great?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A> at: 12/12/02 12:38:51 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 168<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/18/02 11:18:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=100>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Barns</span><hr size=1> Okay, the numbers for the fission chamber of the Liberty Ship are still pretty darn crude, but it looks like I need a moderator.  Blah.  I was really hoping that the density of the UF6 gas at 3000 psi would be high enough to drive the Mean Free Path for fast fission down to a useful number, but unless I am mistaken, it will not.<br>
<br>
Ok, so, we will liberally lace the buffer gas (probably argon) with hydrogen.  At the temperaures I am looking at here, and assuming I am reading the figures right, the scattering cross-section for hydrogen is much higher than it is for almost anything else.  Combined with the hearty layer of beryllium that will be in the reaction chamber wall, and the probable use of Oxygen (which turns out to be pretty neutron reflective as well) as opacity agent in the chamber, I think I can get the neutron flux up high enough to light this puppy reliably.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Another change I am going to advocate is going to U233 as fuel.  U233 seems to have a fast cross-section about 80 percent higher than U235, which will be very useful for this application.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    Pu239 could be even better, but the main trouble is I don't know if there exists a form of Pu239 with the excellent handling properties of UF6, so I want to stick with Uranium if at all possible.  <br>
<br>
I might increase the fraction of U233 above 20 percent, as well.  Higher enrichment helps a lot in getting the vortex to spark up.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
So, I am now thinking of using 50 percent U233.  I will work up more exact numbers in a bit, but I suspect this change will cut the volume requirements of the fuel vaults quite a bit.<br>
<br>
As a note:  20 percent U235 is a considerable proliferation risk, but not outrageous.  50 percent U233 is a very serious proliferation risk indeed.  U233 is a lot easier to seperate from U238 than U235 is, and the base material is a lot &quot;sweeter&quot; as well.  <br>
<br>
To offset this, I would produce the U233 from breeding Th232, and I would &quot;overcook&quot; it so that the U234 percentage is up at the equilibrium number of 7 percent or so.  U234 is TERRIBLE bomb making material, but the Liberty Ship does not care at all, and would actually like the extra neutrons the U234 gives off.  If we are really worried about proliferation, we could deliberately &quot;poison&quot; the U233 fuel with a percentage of U232.  This would add in a zesty dash of gamma rays to the neutrons the U234 gives off.  For much more info on &quot;denaturing&quot; U233, please go read <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.milnet.com/milnet/nukeweap/Nfaq6.html#nfaq6.2"> this page. </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
So, this change to &quot;high octane&quot; fuel is still just as safe as the old stuff, and will make the engines MUCH easier to light.<br>
<br>
&lt;whew&gt;  That was BRUTAL.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Ok, now I know it's the holidays and all, but I hope folks are still thinking about the Liberty Ship, trying to scuttle the design.  The more critical review, the better it becomes!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
