<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> What is the size limit on the low end of the size for the engine? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Using the new U233 fuel, it is much easier to ignite the reaction, so it would seem that it would be easy to make the engine smaller.   However, as was discussed in this thread, one of the critical issues of any NTR is the thrust to weight ratio.  I really worry that it would be difficult to scale any GCNR down too far, because there is a fairly large &quot;fixed mass&quot; involved.  See, you have to have a secure fuel storage scheme, and that means heavy.  <br>
<br>
Since physics places a hard floor on the minimum fissile mass, that fuel storage vault cannot scale below the size needed to safely store the minimum fissile mass along with all related buffer gasses and byproducts. The critical mass of U233F6 is about 50 kilograms, if my math has been done right.  If that is the case, then the fuel vaults on the Liberty Ship thruster are already pretty close to the minimum size possible.<br>
<br>
(Yes, scary as that is, it means that the thrusters will scale upwards better than they scale down.)  <br>
<br>
(Assuming I have done the figures right.)<br>
<br>
So, if the fuel vault is close to the minimum size, then you have to reduce the size of the rest of the thruster.  Lets say you can reduce the total mass of the thruster by half, and then use that smaller model to produce a third of the thrust. (The reason why I think it would produce less than half is due to that pesky squared-cubed law I mentioned earlier.)  <br>
<br>
So, with an empty mass of 60,000 pounds you can get 400,000 pounds of thrust, keeping the Isp at or around 3060.  This is a thrust to weight ratio of 6.7.  <br>
<br>
Use one of these engines, and lets hold the rest of the mass fractions roughly the same as the Liberty Ship.  Assume a launch mass of 300,000 pounds.  120,000 pounds is hydrogen mass, giving a total deltaV of 15 km/sec, allowing full reusability.  Use 60,000 pounds for the structure of the ship, making it very robust and sturdy.  This adds up to a fueled mass, ready to launch, of 240,000 pounds, leaving 60,000 pounds as  cargo.  <br>
<br>
As a note, this is almost exactly the cargo of the Space Shuttle, using a ship less than ten percent the launch weight.  Ain't technology great?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Having only one engine makes launching this thing a real nail-biting proposition, but it certainly seems possible.<br>
<br>
I don't think a gas-cored NTR can scale much smaller than this, but a solid core one sure can, with the loss of a lot of Isp.<br>
<br>
Going all the way down to a 2200 pound cargo is possible, but I don't see any real need for nuclear if you're going that small.  Chemical fuels can get a thousand kilos to orbit just fine, it's only when you want to get real cargo to orbit that it stops scaling.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
But anyhow, if you want to check my math on any of this stuff, I would be very, very happy to accept the help!   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=slntax>SlNTAX</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/23/02 5:58:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=104>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   hey</span><hr size=1> hey MAUK2 its me SlNTAX from the arstechnica forum ! anyways i was wondering what are the limitations of the silca bubble like max heat absorbtion before it melts away .also has there been any studies of combo heat and radation effects on scila ? see im kind of a anal person . the fact that if the bubble breaks you are scewed. it would be better do install some sort of fail safe so if that does happen you dont shoot radioactivity all over the place .also i dont like that fact that we have to haul hydrogen as fuel to propel ourselves around . isnt there a way to convert the raw heat from a nuclear reactor into something we can use to propel ourselves ? because you are always limited how far you can go with the U233 and the hydrogen it would be great if you just take the hydrogen out the the equation and that way less parts means less ways the thing can break or less things can go wrong . <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1686<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/24/02 12:13:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=105>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: hey</span><hr size=1> Well, you have to throw something out the back end in order to <br>
