gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>   i was wondering what are the <br>
limitations of the silca bubble like max heat absorbtion before it melts away <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Silica has good structural and thermal properties for this application, but the important thing to remember is that IT DOESN'T MATTER.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   The physical conditions inside the thruster are so hot that NO KNOWN MATERIAL can withstand them.  We have to design a cooling system to keep the bulb cool that is powerful enough to do the job, and we have to keep the pressure inside and outside the bulb closely balanced.  If we can't do those two things, we could make the bulb out of solid tungsten carbide and it would still evaporate like a snowflake.  The good news is, keeping the bulb cool appears difficult, but doable.  <br>
<br>
The only physical property of that bulb which is absolutely essential is the absorptivity it shows in the light spectra we are working with.  That absorptivity should be as close to zero as we can manage, and as I have shown in this thread, we can do that these days.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> .also has <br>
there been any studies of combo heat and radation effects on scila ?  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  As nebobgranville points out, there have been quite a few studies.  There needs to be a lot more to be certain we have the properties for this appliction well understood.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> it would be better do install <br>
some sort of fail safe so if that does happen you dont shoot radioactivity all over the <br>
place <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
As a matter of fact, I have THREE failsafes on each engine.  Two are triggered by sensors and would be semi-automatic in operation (gas scramble scram and vacuum scram), and one is fully passive with the option for active activation ( boron &quot;shotgun&quot;).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> isnt there a way to convert the raw heat from a nuclear reactor into something <br>
we can use to propel ourselves ? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
As a matter of fact, there is!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    The problem is that even nuclear fission is too weak to develop much in the way of thrust using those methods.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Beamed-core antimatter rockets will someday be able to pull this trick off, but it will be a LONG time from now.   The best that fission can do for us along these lines is the principal used in so-called &quot;foil-core&quot; rockets.  <br>
<br>
<br>
nebobgrenville: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Using a silica coumpound with a very low OH content would help this out.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is correct, and is the problem addressed (among others) by making fused silica with so-called &quot;perfect stoichiometry.&quot;  &lt;sp&gt;     Also, there is a lot of work being done on ultra-pure silica with fluorine doping to increase the transmissivity and lower the absorptivity.<br>
<br>
As for gammas smashing Si-O2 bonds, there is not a lot to be done about that.  The fluorine doping will possibly help a bit with gamma-ray damage, but neutron damage is pretty unavoidable.  I suspect we will simply have to accept a short service life on those lightbulbs and change them frequently.  At least until we develop something better.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
